  "excerpt": "Learn to automate Android web search visually with AskUI & Python! Follow our step-by-step 2026 tutorial.",
  "content": "<p id=\">Want to automate tasks on your Android device just by describing what you see? Forget complex selectors or device specific code. With AskUI's intelligent vision AI agent and Python, you can automate virtually any app on your Android device using simple, human like instructions.</p><p id=\">As the team behind AskUI, we know getting started with mobile automation can sometimes feel tricky. This updated tutorial is the next step in our Android series. It assumes you have already set up your device and now want to write your first real automation using Python to perform a simple web search starting from your home screen.</p><p id=\">We've refined these steps based on our latest software and user feedback to make it as smooth as possible.</p><h2 id=\">Why Automate Android with AskUI?</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Before we dive in, let's quickly recap why AskUI is uniquely suited for Android automation:</p>\n\n<ul id=\"><li id=\"><strong id=\">Truly Universal:</strong> Unlike tools that rely on app code, AskUI sees the screen like you do. This means it works consistently across native apps, web apps, hybrid apps, and even games.</li><li id=\"><strong id=\">Resilient to Changes:</strong> Because it understands visually, minor UI updates like button placement changes often don't break AskUI automations, drastically reducing maintenance.</li><li id=\"><strong id=\">Simple Instructions:</strong> You describe actions based on visual elements such as \"click the button with the text 'Search'\" making scripts intuitive.</li></ul>\n\n<p id=\">You can understand the core tech by reading our guide: <a href=\"https://www.askui.com/blog-posts/what-is-an-intelligent-vision-ai-agent\" target=\"_blank\">What Exactly is an Intelligent Vision AI Agent?</a></p><h2 id=\">Prerequisites: Getting Your Setup Ready</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Before you begin this tutorial, please ensure you have completed these key steps:</p>\n\n<ol start=\"1\" id=\"><li id=\"><strong id=\">Python Installation:</strong> You need Python installed on your computer. Download it from <a href=\"https://www.python.org/\" target=\"_blank\" id=\">python.org</a> if you haven't already. (External Link)</li><li id=\"><strong id=\">AskUI Account:</strong> You'll need AskUI credentials. Sign up for free at <a href=\"http://hub.askui.com/\" target=\"_blank\">AskUI Sign Up</a>. </li><li id=\"><strong id=\">Android Device &amp; Controller Setup:</strong> Your Android device or emulator must be connected via ADB, with \"USB Debugging\" enabled, and the AskUI UI Controller app installed and running.</li></ol>\n\n<p id=\"><strong id=\">If you have not done the Android setup, please follow our detailed guide first:</strong>: <a href=\"https://www.askui.com/blog-posts/tutorial-setting-up-android-devices-for-testing-mobile-apps\" target=\"_blank\" id=\">Tutorial: Setting Up Android Devices for Testing Mobile Apps</a></p><p id=\"> You will also need <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/tools/releases/platform-tools\" target=\"_blank\" id=\">ADB Platform Tools</a>.</p><h2 id=\">Step 1: Initialize Your AskUI Python Project</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Let's create a simple project folder and set up AskUI with Python:</p><p id=\"><strong id=\">1. Create Project Folder:</strong> Open your terminal or command prompt and run:</p><pre id=\"></pre><p id=\"><strong id=\">2. (Recommended) Create a Python Virtual Environment: This keeps your project dependencies isolated</strong></p><pre id=\"></pre><p id=\"><strong id=\">3. Install the AskUI Python Client: Use <code id=\">pip</code> to install the AskUI library</strong>.</p><pre id=\"></pre><p id=\"><strong id=\">4. Create Your Test File: Create a Python file named <code id=\">search_test.py</code></strong>.</p><h2 id=\">Step 2: Writing Your First Android Automation Script in Python</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Open <code id=\">search _test.py </code> and add the following code. We'll use AskUI's Python library to automate opening Chrome, searching for \"spacecraft\" (to match our example images), and verifying the Wikipedia result.</p><p id=\"><strong id=\">Important:</strong> Remember to replace <code id=\">YOUR_WORKSPACE_ID </code> and <code id=\"> YOUR_ACCESS_TOKEN\"</code> with your actual AskUI credentials. For security, it's highly recommended to use environment variables instead of hardcoding credentials in real projects.</p><pre id=\"></pre><h2 id=\">Step 3: Running Your Python Automation</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Make sure your Python virtual environment is activated, your Android device is connected, unlocked, and the AskUI UI Controller app is running. Now, execute your script from the terminal using this command:</p><pre id=\"></pre><p id=\">Watch your Android device! You should see the following steps happen automatically:</p><p id=\"><strong id=\">Our starting point: The Android home screen.</strong></p><figure id=\" class=\"w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-center\" data-rt-type=\"image\" data-rt-align=\"center\"><div id=\"><img src=\"https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6630f90ff7431b0c5b1bb0e7/68fb8f0d3c9f73570fab0c9c_Annotated%20screenshot%20of%20the%20Android%20Emulator%20.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"__wf_reserved_inherit\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\" id=\"></div><figcaption id=\">The automation begins from a typical Android home screen.</figcaption></figure><p id=\">1. AskUI identifies and clicks the \"Chrome\" icon</p><figure id=\" class=\"w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-center\" data-rt-type=\"image\" data-rt-align=\"center\"><div id=\"><img src=\"https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6630f90ff7431b0c5b1bb0e7/68fb8f436e9bc02b69cc9d35_6634d1c7b2d0dd967cfbb589_63725383f633a9b5e72d7a76_l5v8o2pn2msce8dhwfi4.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"__wf_reserved_inherit\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\" id=\"></div><figcaption id=\">AskUI uses its vision capabilities to find the 'Chrome' icon, even among other icons, as indicated by the red bounding box.</figcaption></figure><p id=\">2. Chrome opens, and AskUI finds and clicks the search bar.</p><figure id=\" class=\"w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-center\" data-rt-type=\"image\" data-rt-align=\"center\"><div id=\"><img src=\"https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6630f90ff7431b0c5b1bb0e7/68fb8fa52fcda61ac3bf57af_Main%20page%20of%20the%20Chrome%20app%20.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"__wf_reserved_inherit\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\" id=\"></div><figcaption id=\">The Chrome app launches, and AskUI locates the 'Search or type web address' text field visually.</figcaption></figure><p id=\">3. AskUI types \"spacecraft,\" presses Enter, and successfully identifies the \"Spacecraft - Wikipedia\" text on the results page.</p><figure id=\" class=\"w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-center\" data-rt-type=\"image\" data-rt-align=\"center\"><div id=\"><img src=\"https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6630f90ff7431b0c5b1bb0e7/68fb8fb89ca3bb668946c184_Search%20result%20of%20%27spacecraft%27%20.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"__wf_reserved_inherit\" width=\"auto\" height=\"auto\" id=\"></div><figcaption id=\">Success! The automation completes the search and verifies the Wikipedia link on the results page.</figcaption></figure><p id=\">If your console logs \"Search successful! Wikipedia link found,\" congratulations. You've successfully automated a web search on Android using AskUI and Python.</p><h2 id=\">Troubleshooting &amp; Tips from Our Experience</h2>\n\n<p id=\">Here are a couple of common issues:</p>\n\n<ul id=\"><li id=\"><strong id=\">\"Element not found\":</strong> Mobile UIs vary. If AskUI can't find your \"Chrome\" icon or the search bar, use the <code id=\">await askui_core.annotate()</code> command temporarily in your script. Run it. It will generate an annotated screenshot (<code id=\">annotation.png</code>) showing how AskUI sees the screen. Adjust your element descriptions (<code id=\">icon().with_text() , </code><code id=\">textfield()</code>, etc.) based on what AskUI sees.</li><li id=\"><strong id=\">Timing Issues:</strong> Apps can be slow. Use <code id=\">await asyncio.sleep(seconds)</code> generously, especially after launching apps or triggering actions.</li></ul><h2 id=\">Final Thoughts</h2>\n\n<p id=\">You've just automated a web search on Android using Python and the power of intelligent vision! This simple example only scratches the surface. Because AskUI interacts visually, you can use the same principles to automate virtually any task within any Android application, no matter how complex or dynamic its UI might be.</p><p id=\">Ready to automate more? Explore our <a href=\"https://docs.askui.com/\" target=\"_blank\" id=\">AskUI Documentation</a> for more commands and advanced techniques. Happy automating.</p><h2 id=\">About the AskUI Content Team</h2>\n\n<p id=\">This article was written and fact checked by the AskUI Content Team. Our team works closely with engineers and product experts to bring you accurate, insightful, and practical information about the world of Agentic AI. We are passionate about making technology more accessible to everyone.</p>",
